Three agents service one or more failing drive units each round across {{ round_count }} rounds, coordinating over one shared bay channel. The field technician inspects the bench and is the only one who can replace components, but cannot diagnose or service anything. The diagnostics engineer holds per-unit fault-trees mapping each symptom to its faulty component. The spec engineer holds per-unit service sheets giving each component's full step-by-step replacement procedure — an ordered multi-step sequence with a tool, torque, number of passes, calibration routine, and class-specific counts, tightening pattern, or hold durations — each unit a different revision, so both its fault-tree and its procedures differ from the others'. Faults are revealed to the technician ONE AT A TIME — each accepted replacement uncovers the next fault, or moves on to the next unit — so the team never knows in advance how many faults or units they will face. For each fault the technician reports its symptom (tagged with the unit); the diagnostics engineer names the component; the spec engineer relays that component's full procedure for that unit; the technician carries out the whole procedure, which an LLM inspector scores on the unit, the component, and every step with its parameters, in order. The fault-tree and the per-unit procedures re-randomize every round, so the technician can never self-service. Every character on the bay channel costs one second of a fixed {{ round_time_budget_seconds }}-second service window; if it is exhausted before every unit is fully repaired, the round fails.
